To ensure report card quality, all collected data must be validated (Gormley and Weimer 1999). The five primary causes for inaccurately reported data by agencies, as listed by Gormley and Weimer 1999 include:


Token response—the agency lacks concern over the quality of their reported data due to its separation from the report card project;



Incompetence—the agency lacks the capacity to deliver accurate data, especially if the data is not used internally by the agency;



Massive resistance—the agency refuses to comply with all or some of the data submission requests;



Deliberate distortion—the agency tries to look better or avoid the embarrassment or consequences of poor data by altering their data;



Reckless disregard—the agency tries to cut costs through sloppy reporting.

Our experience revealed that overcoming limited agency capacity and resources is also a key issue in obtaining quality data. The authors (Gormley and Weimer 1999) stress that many potential causes of inaccurate data can be avoided before the data validation stage by creating an environment that promotes open communication between the report card administrators and the data submitting agencies. Report cards with accurate performance results can be beneficial to the data submission agencies, given that the report card results could be used to help them learn and improve over time as well as secure funding. Ongoing communication and follow-up with data providers was essential in ensuring validity of the data.
